Note on the BPF program source file (`src/iomoments.bpf.c`): that single
translation unit is dual-licensed `(GPL-2.0-only OR AGPL-3.0-or-later)`
via SPDX header, and declares `char _license[] SEC("license") = "GPL";`
in-source. This is a kernel-ABI requirement — Linux's
`license_is_gpl_compatible()` allowlist (`kernel/bpf/core.c`) does not
recognize the literal string "AGPL", even though AGPL-3.0 is legally
GPL-compatible via AGPL §13, and most tracing helpers iomoments needs
are GPL-only. The GPL-2.0-only branch unlocks those helpers at verifier
time; the AGPL-3.0-or-later branch keeps the project's overall license
identity consistent. See `DECISIONS.md` D001 for the full rationale.


No external contributions accepted
----------------------------------

Ed Hodapp is the sole author and sole copyright holder of iomoments.
External contributions (pull requests, patches, and similar upstream
submissions) are **not accepted** at this time. Bug reports via GitHub
issues are welcome; fixes described in issues may be reimplemented by
the author. This follows the SQLite model and matches the sibling
open-source projects.

Consolidated copyright ownership preserves future licensing flexibility.
In particular, Ed retains the right to issue private commercial grants
that permit the iomoments algorithms to be re-implemented inside
proprietary sibling projects (e.g., bare-metal ARM64 assembly codebases
where AGPL contamination is incompatible with product licensing), under
terms negotiated case-by-case. Accepting external contributions under
AGPL without a CLA would lock that option down.

The Pébay (2008) update rules and the underlying method of moments are
public prior art (Sandia SAND2008-6212; Pearson 1894). AGPL protects
specific code expression only, not algorithms. Re-implementations
written from the Pébay paper rather than translated from the iomoments
C source are not encumbered by this project's license.

Commercial deployments that cannot accept AGPL's network-copyleft (§13)
obligations — SaaS operators, OEM integrators, and anyone embedding
iomoments in a closed-source observability product — should contact Ed
for a commercial license / consulting engagement.
